        output='## Distinguishing Starlink Subscriber, Service Line, and Supported Accounts\n\nThe SpaceX S-1 filing (filed May 20, 2026) defines these three terms in its glossary, and they measure fundamentally different things — two relate to Starlink\'s physical broadband connectivity business, while the third relates to the X/Grok software platforms.\n\n### 1. Precise Definitions (from the S-1 glossary)\n\n**Service Line** — "an individual instance of Starlink broadband internet service provisioned under a subscription plan, generally associated with a specific Starlink User Terminal or group of terminals, and **billed according to Starlink\'s service plans and terms of service**. The number of Service Lines is distinct from the number of unique devices, account holders, end users, or physical persons."\n\n- This is the broadest Starlink-side metric. It captures *every* billed instance of service — consumer, business, enterprise, and government.\n- The filing explicitly notes that one person/entity can hold multiple Service Lines (e.g., a Residential line plus a separate Roam line = two Service Lines), and conversely multiple people in a household can share one Service Line.\n\n**Starlink Subscriber** — "a unique Service Line that is directly assigned to a Starlink.com account registered to a person or entity that **does not have a direct, negotiated agreement with the Starlink sales team**."\n\n- This is a **subset** of Service Lines. It includes Personal plans (Residential, Roam) and Business plans (Local Priority, Global Priority), but **excludes managed enterprise and government customers** with negotiated contracts in aviation, maritime, land mobility, fixed sites, and government entities.\n- The filing states: "We calculate Starlink Subscribers for a period as the number of unique Service Lines at the end of the period" — but only counting those Service Lines that meet the non-negotiated-account criterion.\n- Reported count: **~10.3 million** as of March 31, 2026 (up from ~5.0 million a year earlier).\n\n**Supported accounts** — "when used in the context of our X platform and Grok, a human, bot or similar account that logged into the X platform or Grok. **The total number of supported accounts may include fake, spam or bot accounts if they are active.**"\n\n- This is an entirely separate metric tied to the X/Grok software platforms (acquired via the xAI/X Holdings mergers), not to Starlink connectivity.\n- Reported count: **over 1.3 billion** supported accounts active in the LTM ended March 31, 2026 (vs. ~550 million MAUs and only ~6.3 million active paid subscribers across X Premium/Premium+ and SuperGrok tiers).\n\n### 2. Which is most analogous to a revenue-generating customer?\n\n**Service Line** is the most analogous to a revenue-generating customer.\n\nReasoning:\n- The glossary definition explicitly ties a Service Line to billing: it is "billed according to Starlink\'s service plans and terms of service." Every Service Line is, by definition, a billed revenue-generating unit.\n- It is the **most inclusive** revenue-generating metric on the Starlink side, capturing consumer, business, enterprise, and government customers alike.\n- Starlink Subscriber is *also* revenue-generating (the filing computes Starlink Subscriber ARPU as "service revenue generated from Starlink Subscribers during the period" divided by average subscribers), but it is a **narrower** subset that deliberately excludes negotiated enterprise/government contracts. So while each Starlink Subscriber is a paying customer, the metric understates the total revenue-generating customer base.\n- Supported accounts is **not** analogous to a revenue-generating customer. The filing itself warns that the count "may include fake, spam or bot accounts," and only ~6.3 million of the 1.3+ billion supported accounts are active paid subscribers. It is a reach/scale metric, not a billing metric.\n\n### 3. Which has the highest count, and why?\n\n**Supported accounts** has by far the highest count — **over 1.3 billion**, versus ~10.3 million Starlink Subscribers (and a slightly larger but still tens-of-millions figure for total Service Lines, which is not separately reported).\n\nWhy supported accounts is the largest:\n- **Broadest definitional scope.** It captures *any* account — human, bot, or similar — that simply logged into X or Grok during the trailing twelve months. The filing expressly permits fake, spam, and bot accounts to be counted as long as they are "active."\n- **Software/login metric, not a hardware/billing metric.** Unlike Service Lines, supported accounts require no physical terminal deployment, no subscription payment, and no negotiated contract — only a login event.\n- **Spans two large consumer platforms.** X and Grok collectively reach a global user base orders of magnitude larger than Starlink\'s deployed terminal base.\n- **Decoupled from monetization.** The filing discloses that only ~550 million of the 1.3+ billion are MAUs, and only ~6.3 million are paying subscribers — confirming that the headline supported-accounts figure vastly overstates the revenue-generating base.\n\nBy contrast, Service Lines and Starlink Subscribers are constrained by physical Starlink User Terminal deployment and active subscription billing, which naturally caps the count in the tens of millions rather than billions.\n\n### Summary Table\n\n| Metric | Definition (essence) | Revenue-generating? | Count (as of 3/31/2026 or LTM) |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **Service Line** | Billed instance of Starlink service on a terminal | Yes — explicitly "billed according to Starlink\'s service plans" | Not separately reported; superset of Starlink Subscribers |\n| **Starlink Subscriber** | Service Line on a non-negotiated Starlink.com account (excludes enterprise/gov\'t) | Yes — subset of Service Lines; ARPU computed from this base | ~10.3 million |\n| **Supported accounts** | Any login (human/bot/spam) on X or Grok in trailing 12 months | No — includes fake/spam/bot accounts; only ~6.3M of 1.3B+ are paid | Over 1.3 billion |\n\n**Bottom line:** Service Line is the closest analog to a revenue-generating customer (it is the billed unit and the most inclusive), Starlink Subscriber is a revenue-generating subset that excludes negotiated enterprise/government contracts, and supported accounts is a non-monetized reach metric that nonetheless posts the highest count because it counts any active login — including bots and spam — across the much larger X/Grok user base.\n\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "Space Exploration Technologies Corp. (SpaceX) Form S-1, filed May 20, 2026 — glossary definitions of \'Starlink Subscriber,\' \'Service Line,\' and \'supported accounts\'; Starlink Subscriber counts; X/Grok supported accounts, MAUs, and paid subscriber counts"\n    }\n  ]\n}',
